## Proposed Changes

### Backend Infrastructure & Configuration

#### [MODIFY] [env.js](file:///c:/Users/bibha/Desktop/sahayog-sarthi/backend/src/config/env.js)
*   Register `ENABLE_TELEGRAM_BOT` as an optional configuration variable.
*   Expose `ENABLE_TELEGRAM_BOT` in the exported configuration object, defaulting to `false` when missing or not set to `'true'`.

#### [MODIFY] [telegramService.js](file:///c:/Users/bibha/Desktop/sahayog-sarthi/backend/src/services/telegramService.js)
*   Import `env` from configuration module instead of raw `process.env`.
*   Wrap bot initialization block: Only instantiate `TelegramBot` when `ENABLE_TELEGRAM_BOT` is `'true'` (or equivalent config flag) and `TELEGRAM_BOT_TOKEN` is present.
*   Determine polling activation flag: Disable `polling` (set `polling: false`) during tests (`NODE_ENV === 'test'`), local development (`NODE_ENV === 'development'`), and CI/CD pipelines (`process.env.CI` or `GITHUB_ACTIONS`).
*   Ensure the helper function `sendBookingAlertToWorker` returns early if the bot is not initialized, preserving safe mock-like fallback behavior.

#### [MODIFY] [.env.example](file:///c:/Users/bibha/Desktop/sahayog-sarthi/backend/.env.example)
*   Add the `ENABLE_TELEGRAM_BOT` documentation and set the default template value to `false`.

#### [MODIFY] [.env](file:///c:/Users/bibha/Desktop/sahayog-sarthi/backend/.env)
*   Add `ENABLE_TELEGRAM_BOT=false` to prevent background polling threads from starting automatically during local development.

